    <title>Combined summary - DRAFT: interactive tx construction protocol</title>
    <updated>2023-06-02T23:26:11.760000+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2020-February/002515.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email thread discusses various proposals related to the PoDLE signature commitment, multi-channel open in Lightning Network, and simplification of the dual-funding proposal. The PoDLE mechanism is used in JoinMarket to stop trivial global snooping, and a proposed addition of a second commitment requirement aims to limit the use of a commitment's validity between an initiator and a single peer. In the Lightning Network, the modified PoDLE signature commitment requires every initiator to include at least one of their own inputs in the transaction. The conversation thread discusses the implementation of nLockTime in C-lightning and proposes a dual-funding protocol update for the Lightning Network. The proposed update allows the initiator to announce its own tip to sign the funding transaction, even if the receiver's tip is backward, with multi-party transactions construction. Additionally, anti-fee sniping and mutual closing transactions are discussed. The Lightning Network protocol involves several message types and subtypes, and the validity of inputs/outputs is not checked until both peers have sent consecutive 'tx_complete' messages.The conversation between Antoine, Lisa Neigut, and Max revolves around the integration of nLockTime into C-lightning as a part of the Lightning Network protocol. Antoine proposed a transaction chain construction to address utxos snooping. Lisa shared feedback on the dual-funding proposal, suggesting simplifying it into smaller chunks. It is important to note that the validity of inputs/outputs is not checked until both peers have sent consecutive `tx_complete` messages. The proposed change in the dual-funding protocol allows for the removal of inputs and outputs.The Lightning-dev mailing list has proposed a new RBF (Replace-By-Fee) fee bumping proposal for Lightning Network transactions. The proposal suggests that each "fee_step" should add 1/4 to the initial transaction feerate, which should exceed the minimum transaction relay setting as per Rule 4 of BIP125. The recipient must check that the new fee does not exceed the sender's current balance minus reserve after being applied to the splice transaction.The proposal in question can be found on GitHub, where interested parties can view the code and participate in the discussion. Additionally, the Lightning Network RFC repository has a pull request related to this proposal, which can also be viewed and commented on. Those interested in contributing to the discussion can join the Lightning-dev mailing list or contact the proposal author directly via email.</summary>
